"Oar, oar, oar you're boat"?

@Francis 

I mean “more to chew on” with my use of “crunchy “ in this context.

Do emus chew?

@My dear archaeoprof,

If it's any comfort, I also find them more difficult than I used to, but I think it's because they sometimes play fast and loose with the cluing and because there are so many references I just haven't the foggiest idea about. Second-string TV actors, brand names, auto makes, teenage slang -- to me there's too much junk. The puzzle used to challenge with clever wordplay and interesting entries, including things not everyone would know but that would be worth learning. 

Keep at it! All the best to you.

@CalGal 
Speck is a delicious ham that's sort of like a smoked prosciutto. Serrano is the Spanish version of prosciutto. (I guess all my descriptions of ham use prosciutto as the starting point.)

"Erm" is in my experience the written British version of the American "um"—because many British accents (or maybe "some" is more accurate) are non-rhotic, "erm" is pronounced much the same way as "um" is in many American accents.

@Francis 
Well it's not in the Scrabble Dictionary, which contains British words such as colour and favour, and a host of words nobody would ever say. One of my favourites is vug, defined as a hole in a rock. If I ever found a rock with a hole, I would never say, "Look at the vug." I would say, "Look at the hole in that rock." 
Likewise, I would never say "erm."

@Becca 
Wonderful.
Thank you!

@CaptainQuahog I know LIMN from the bee :). 

I wonder if the answer was actually ABYSs (which made total sense!) and MAXIMUM was MAXIMUs (plausible I think!) if team MAXIMUM people would have been up in arms.  Actually I know the answer lol.  

I was pretty annoyed because ABYSs was such a strong answer for that clue but I lived to solve another day! LOL

